A potential bug could be that `getInsertBlock` returns a block that is not a valid insertion point. For example, if it returns the entry block of the function, but some of the values used to build the vectorized instruction are defined within a more deeply nested block, then those values would not be available at the insertion point.

The `getInsertBlock` function has this logic:
```cpp
// If the new instruction is a PHI node, it should be inserted into the
// beginning of the basic block of the other PHI nodes.
if (isa<PHINode>(V[0]))
  return cast<PHINode>(V[0])->getParent();
```
This seems correct for PHI nodes. For other instructions, it finds a common dominator.

The problem might be in how the vectorizer decides *which* instructions to vectorize together. If it groups instructions that lead to an invalid placement, it will fail.

The `BoUpSLP` vectorizer has a function `canMapToVector` which checks if a set of instructions can be vectorized. It checks for dominance and other constraints. A bug here could lead to incorrect vectorization attempts.

The core of the issue is likely related to hoisting instructions. When vectorizing instructions from multiple basic blocks, the new vector instruction is placed in a common dominator. All operands to this new instruction must also be available (dominate) at this insertion point. If an operand is an instruction defined in one of the original blocks, it needs to be hoisted as well, or the vector instruction needs to be sunk.

